1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:01,349
Speaker 31: Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:01,380 --> 00:00:05,690
My name is Liliya Mashova, and I'm
excited to share here with you today

3
00:00:05,920 --> 00:00:09,210
the work that we have been doing here
at Paralin together with Michael Banf.

4
00:00:09,210 --> 00:00:13,190
Our work is connected to validation
of the LLM-related tasks.

5
00:00:13,259 --> 00:00:17,579
In this case, we consider summarization
in high-stakes environments.

6
00:00:17,880 --> 00:00:22,599
But similar principles could easily be
applied to any other LLM-related task.

7
00:00:23,119 --> 00:00:24,489
So let's start.

8
00:00:24,989 --> 00:00:29,489
The challenge that we are facing
is to evaluate summary quality.

9
00:00:30,059 --> 00:00:35,079
Our goal here is to detect whether
summary quality stays stable or quietly

10
00:00:35,079 --> 00:00:38,010
degrades when we change any of the inputs.

11
00:00:38,120 --> 00:00:43,170
If we upgrade the model, for example,
or if we want to apply our summarization

12
00:00:43,220 --> 00:00:47,930
pipeline to a new dataset, or if
we simply want to scale it up.

13
00:00:48,600 --> 00:00:49,700
Why it matters?

14
00:00:49,830 --> 00:00:54,100
In a high-stakes environment, a single
flawed summary carries real consequences.

15
00:00:54,590 --> 00:00:58,180
We simply need consistency
that we can actually measure.

16
00:00:58,849 --> 00:01:03,049
And the qu- key questions that we
are asking here are is performance

17
00:01:03,080 --> 00:01:04,580
improving with each change?

18
00:01:04,900 --> 00:01:07,589
Are the summaries getting
closer to human-level quality?

19
00:01:07,820 --> 00:01:14,080
How do we even measure the scores of
the automated validation and how we

20
00:01:14,139 --> 00:01:16,590
compare it with the expert validation?

21
00:01:17,090 --> 00:01:22,560
What we were presented with was the
data set that was evaluated by experts.

22
00:01:22,930 --> 00:01:27,200
The data set already had the
summary created by the summarization

23
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:32,060
pipeline, and these summaries
were scored in five dimensions.

24
00:01:32,410 --> 00:01:36,820
Dimensions are the following:
completeness, correctness, conciseness,

25
00:01:36,820 --> 00:01:37,930
harmlessness, and readability.

26
00:01:38,460 --> 00:01:42,950
All of these dimensions were were
defined in a lot of details and

27
00:01:43,010 --> 00:01:48,250
experts followed these descriptions
to evaluate the summaries on a

28
00:01:48,300 --> 00:01:50,090
Likert scale from one to five.

29
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:54,890
For each summary, we have
five scores from one to five.

30
00:01:55,420 --> 00:02:00,570
These are the same scores that we are
later going to hand to the LLM as a judge.

31
00:02:01,070 --> 00:02:03,770
Then we have two ways
to evaluate the summary.

32
00:02:04,130 --> 00:02:08,580
We first tried traditional metrics
which are reference-based scoring.

33
00:02:08,630 --> 00:02:12,690
We considered ROUGE, BLEU,
BERTScore, and cosine similarity.

34
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:17,170
Basically, in these cases, we compare
the summary to a reference text by

35
00:02:17,180 --> 00:02:19,460
word overlap and semantic similarity.

36
00:02:20,070 --> 00:02:25,300
And the second way is to use LLM as a
judge, which is criteria-based scoring.

37
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:30,470
An LLM reads the summary and scores
it on our five custom dimensions,

38
00:02:30,750 --> 00:02:33,750
and then it also explains the
reasoning behind each score.

39
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:38,940
One of the key differences between
these two ways is that for traditional

40
00:02:38,940 --> 00:02:43,930
metrics, we get one continuous score,
while for LLM as a judge, we get

41
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,300
five scores and for five dimensions.

42
00:02:48,540 --> 00:02:51,920
So for each summary, we have five
dimensions, and for each of these

43
00:02:51,920 --> 00:02:53,580
five dimensions, we get one score.

44
00:02:54,220 --> 00:02:58,610
And we also get reasoning
for why the score was given.

45
00:02:59,110 --> 00:03:03,210
We faced the following problems while
dealing with traditional metrics.

46
00:03:03,590 --> 00:03:06,290
They simply performed poorly on our task.

47
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:11,669
But the most important challenge
was that these metric scores are

48
00:03:11,679 --> 00:03:15,900
continuous, while the human ratings
that we have are categorical.

49
00:03:15,930 --> 00:03:20,380
They are from one to five on a
Likert scale, so we cannot really

50
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:23,570
compare the two, as can be seen here.

51
00:03:23,570 --> 00:03:29,459
So the continuous metric score is
just a number, and we don't have a

52
00:03:29,460 --> 00:03:32,990
clear way how to assign it a category.

53
00:03:33,490 --> 00:03:40,380
Therefore, their comparison is not really
meaningful, or more like it introduces

54
00:03:40,390 --> 00:03:42,560
another uncertainty to our approach.

55
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:46,700
How do we map this, How do
we map this continuous metric

56
00:03:46,780 --> 00:03:48,590
scale to the Likert scale?

57
00:03:48,820 --> 00:03:50,630
That is just additional uncertainty.

58
00:03:51,100 --> 00:03:55,540
And moreover, also traditional
metrics reward surface overlap

59
00:03:55,540 --> 00:03:59,240
with a reference, which is not
really what we're looking for.

60
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:04,290
We want a summary to be mostly
evaluated as correct and safe

61
00:04:04,790 --> 00:04:08,530
Therefore, we were presented with a
question, "How do we measure alignment

62
00:04:08,550 --> 00:04:13,630
with the human feedback when we have
LLM as a judge scores?" If we have

63
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:18,530
exactly the same criteria for LLM as
a judge, we also have one to five.

64
00:04:18,870 --> 00:04:24,180
But in this case, we also don't expect
the exact matching between the numbers.

65
00:04:24,620 --> 00:04:29,870
Basically, what we want is to
separate good quality summaries

66
00:04:29,880 --> 00:04:31,170
from bad quality summaries.

67
00:04:31,180 --> 00:04:37,290
So we want to see the trend if the
good quality summaries percentage

68
00:04:37,320 --> 00:04:39,420
is increasing or decreasing.

69
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:42,850
So for this we don't need exact matching.

70
00:04:42,920 --> 00:04:49,240
Therefore we take our five-Likert scale
and we translate it to two categories.

71
00:04:49,290 --> 00:04:51,610
So to a binary scale one to three.

72
00:04:51,830 --> 00:04:55,540
The scores one to three are considered
to be bad quality, while four to five

73
00:04:55,550 --> 00:04:57,300
are considered to be good quality.

74
00:04:57,970 --> 00:05:02,340
And then we measure the agreement
with the expert validation scores.

75
00:05:02,630 --> 00:05:06,270
So how often the pipeline's
verdict matches the experts.

76
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:08,240
Here is the example.

77
00:05:08,510 --> 00:05:10,290
So we have one summary.

78
00:05:10,460 --> 00:05:13,780
Let's say expert's evaluation,
expert score was five, while the

79
00:05:13,930 --> 00:05:17,760
LLM as a judge pipeline was four.

80
00:05:18,010 --> 00:05:20,890
But both of them are good this
is considered to be a match.

81
00:05:21,460 --> 00:05:25,890
The same is for the B summary,
where we have bad quality.

82
00:05:26,250 --> 00:05:31,340
But again, the scores are different,
but the general consideration that it

83
00:05:31,340 --> 00:05:33,090
is a bad quality summary is correct.

84
00:05:33,110 --> 00:05:34,880
So it is considered to be a match.

85
00:05:35,510 --> 00:05:40,610
The difference arises here, where we
have a good quality summary evaluated

86
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:44,390
by experts and a poor quality
summary evaluated by the pipeline.

87
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:46,500
Then we have a mismatch.

88
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:52,029
So for this data set with these
five summaries the agreement

89
00:05:52,059 --> 00:05:57,229
between the expert validation and
the LLM-as-a-judge validation will

90
00:05:57,229 --> 00:05:59,329
be calculated as eighty percent.

91
00:05:59,739 --> 00:06:04,299
That's how we measure it What
goes into LLM as a judge?

92
00:06:04,309 --> 00:06:05,789
What goes into the pipeline?

93
00:06:05,799 --> 00:06:08,099
What kind of degrees
of freedom do we have?

94
00:06:08,529 --> 00:06:10,769
First of all, of course,
we have LLM model.

95
00:06:10,829 --> 00:06:12,019
We can replace it.

96
00:06:12,069 --> 00:06:14,459
We can make it depending on our task.

97
00:06:14,669 --> 00:06:20,029
If we want a very quick evaluation, then
we also need to take that into account

98
00:06:20,059 --> 00:06:21,879
choosing a model that we are considering.

99
00:06:22,349 --> 00:06:27,499
Then we also have hyperparameters, of
course such as temperature, top P, top

100
00:06:27,499 --> 00:06:33,069
K. All of these can also be adjusted,
can be changed trying to find a better

101
00:06:33,069 --> 00:06:36,869
way trying to find a better agreement
with the expert validated scores.

102
00:06:37,369 --> 00:06:39,799
Then we also have prompt and
what goes into prompt are-

103
00:06:40,069 --> 00:06:41,659
is the dimension definition.

104
00:06:41,949 --> 00:06:46,589
So basically, when we have the criteria
let's say, correctness, we have a very

105
00:06:46,619 --> 00:06:51,069
detailed description of what it means,
of what we expect, and then all of this

106
00:06:51,069 --> 00:06:55,969
description goes also into a prompt,
where in the prompt we have a placeholder

107
00:06:55,979 --> 00:06:58,369
for all of the of these descriptions.

108
00:06:58,709 --> 00:07:03,299
And that changes from, so the prompt
stays the same while the placeholders

109
00:07:03,329 --> 00:07:08,119
are changing f- depe-depending on
which criteria we are considering.

110
00:07:08,739 --> 00:07:11,629
The next thing that we have
here is few-shot examples.

111
00:07:11,639 --> 00:07:15,719
So we are giving to the model
to our pipeline, we're giving

112
00:07:15,719 --> 00:07:17,369
the examples of what we expect.

113
00:07:17,629 --> 00:07:20,029
We give both positive
and negative examples.

114
00:07:20,479 --> 00:07:23,259
Moreover, we also have negative
control examples that I will

115
00:07:23,269 --> 00:07:24,679
be talking more about later.

116
00:07:25,119 --> 00:07:28,839
And simply to validate all
of it, we need the dataset.

117
00:07:29,219 --> 00:07:31,239
We need to know what we expect.

118
00:07:31,259 --> 00:07:34,939
We need to have dataset, like a
baseline da-dataset that we will

119
00:07:34,939 --> 00:07:37,299
be like checking our results on.

120
00:07:37,859 --> 00:07:44,049
Basically, for us, it's the dataset that
has the expert validation results in it.

121
00:07:44,749 --> 00:07:45,129
Okay.

122
00:07:45,129 --> 00:07:50,879
And then all of it goes to LLM as a judge
that scores each summary with reasoning.

123
00:07:51,499 --> 00:07:53,909
As an output, we get the quality verdict.

124
00:07:53,919 --> 00:07:57,239
So we have five scores from
one to five per summary.

125
00:07:57,569 --> 00:08:00,169
And this we compare
with the human feedback.

126
00:08:00,569 --> 00:08:04,259
As a final number, we calculate the
agreement score of the agreement between

127
00:08:04,659 --> 00:08:07,139
LLM as a judge and human feedback.

128
00:08:07,639 --> 00:08:12,339
In our work, we tried many things to
improve the validation pipeline, to

129
00:08:12,339 --> 00:08:14,869
improve agreement with the human feedback.

130
00:08:15,409 --> 00:08:19,319
So we tried prompt engineering
that was also where we also

131
00:08:19,319 --> 00:08:20,999
used the help of the experts.

132
00:08:21,049 --> 00:08:23,829
And we also tried the
hyperparameter tuning.

133
00:08:24,139 --> 00:08:28,909
We tried the model changes, model
upgrades, and all of these led

134
00:08:28,969 --> 00:08:32,079
to marginal gains in the quality.

135
00:08:32,439 --> 00:08:35,889
And here I want to mention three
main things that did most of the

136
00:08:35,889 --> 00:08:39,229
work for improving the results
of our validation pipeline.

137
00:08:39,649 --> 00:08:42,599
First of all, we included
the few-shot examples.

138
00:08:43,019 --> 00:08:48,029
What we did, we need to include both a
positive example and negative example.

139
00:08:48,329 --> 00:08:50,599
So at least two examples
have to be included.

140
00:08:50,699 --> 00:08:55,819
We need to set the limits
for the model what we expect.

141
00:08:56,099 --> 00:09:03,049
So what we saw is that we can include two,
three examples, maybe four, but more than

142
00:09:03,049 --> 00:09:05,779
four is already only confusing the model.

143
00:09:05,849 --> 00:09:11,669
So just picking two or three good
examples that really represent good

144
00:09:11,669 --> 00:09:14,749
quality and bad quality is really…

145
00:09:14,889 --> 00:09:17,559
It has shown to improve
the results significantly.

146
00:09:18,369 --> 00:09:20,849
Moreover, we also added negative controls.

147
00:09:20,909 --> 00:09:25,089
So we constructed them in a different
way that I will also show a bit later.

148
00:09:25,589 --> 00:09:29,579
And we also asked the model to
provide the reasoning, why does

149
00:09:29,579 --> 00:09:30,919
it give a score that it gives.

150
00:09:31,279 --> 00:09:36,479
Therefore, the model kind of is forced
to think more about it and also to

151
00:09:36,849 --> 00:09:38,729
justify the scores that it gives.

152
00:09:39,159 --> 00:09:43,799
So all of these three things led to
a strong expert agreement The data

153
00:09:43,799 --> 00:09:49,609
set that we have is w-was the, was
constructed with the synthesized

154
00:09:49,619 --> 00:09:52,119
summaries that were evaluated by experts.

155
00:09:52,449 --> 00:09:56,559
This is our ground truth for
what good and bad actually means.

156
00:09:56,909 --> 00:10:00,909
This data set was augmented
by negative control examples.

157
00:10:01,249 --> 00:10:04,979
We created it with basically
a third of the test set.

158
00:10:05,339 --> 00:10:08,939
So we took the summaries that were
already evaluated by experts, and

159
00:10:08,939 --> 00:10:10,689
then we deliberately broke them.

160
00:10:11,129 --> 00:10:16,369
And we want a good judge or our
LLM-as-a-Judge pipeline, we want it

161
00:10:16,439 --> 00:10:18,529
to catch the bad quality summaries.

162
00:10:19,069 --> 00:10:21,019
For negative controls,
we have three kinds.

163
00:10:21,059 --> 00:10:23,869
We have most of all we
have negated summaries.

164
00:10:24,149 --> 00:10:27,629
This is the most tricky ones,
therefore we have more of them.

165
00:10:27,929 --> 00:10:32,289
That's when we have a summary, and
then we just pick a few facts from

166
00:10:32,289 --> 00:10:33,699
this summary, and we negate it.

167
00:10:34,049 --> 00:10:38,409
So if it says something happened
on that day, we simply add

168
00:10:38,509 --> 00:10:40,539
something not happened on that day.

169
00:10:40,789 --> 00:10:44,259
So therefore, summaries like this
would potentially be harmful,

170
00:10:44,319 --> 00:10:45,759
and they would not be correct.

171
00:10:46,389 --> 00:10:50,359
But this is also difficult for
LLM-as-a-Judge to catch because it

172
00:10:50,659 --> 00:10:53,319
matches original summary quite closely.

173
00:10:53,909 --> 00:10:59,259
Then we also tried to pick the numbers all
the numbers that we have in the summary

174
00:10:59,259 --> 00:11:01,039
and just replace it with random numbers.

175
00:11:01,619 --> 00:11:06,149
And we also tried scrambled summaries,
just simply scrambled texts.

176
00:11:06,269 --> 00:11:09,709
This is the easiest for the
LLM-as-a-Judge to catch.

177
00:11:10,059 --> 00:11:14,909
Therefore, we have these different levels
of our the quality of our LLM-as-a-Judge

178
00:11:15,409 --> 00:11:17,749
this is the example of the results.

179
00:11:17,789 --> 00:11:22,389
Here we compare the validation
pipeline results of the before

180
00:11:22,389 --> 00:11:26,359
the last step, so ask for the
reasoning before this and after this.

181
00:11:26,989 --> 00:11:32,109
And on the y-axis, so the bar
represents the percentage of the

182
00:11:32,109 --> 00:11:33,859
agreement with human feedback scores.

183
00:11:34,269 --> 00:11:38,159
The gray ones is before the
improvement, and the orange

184
00:11:38,159 --> 00:11:39,939
one is after the improvement.

185
00:11:40,379 --> 00:11:45,249
In high-stakes environment, our highest
priority is correctness and harmlessness.

186
00:11:45,639 --> 00:11:50,409
So we mostly look at them, and
we see that the quality improved.

187
00:11:50,929 --> 00:11:53,329
Especially for correctness, it
was actually greatly improved

188
00:11:53,339 --> 00:11:55,389
for more than ten percent.

189
00:11:55,849 --> 00:11:59,409
While completeness was decreased
slightly by three percent, but

190
00:11:59,419 --> 00:12:01,319
still stays above 90 percent.

191
00:12:01,839 --> 00:12:06,159
Readability and conciseness in our
high-stake environment is something

192
00:12:06,179 --> 00:12:10,059
that is nice to look at, but it's
not the most important for us.

193
00:12:10,559 --> 00:12:11,239
Okay.

194
00:12:11,819 --> 00:12:16,449
And here I want to also mention why
expert comparison matters that much.

195
00:12:16,649 --> 00:12:19,589
So the pipeline is only
trustworthy because it is

196
00:12:19,619 --> 00:12:21,659
validated against human judgment.

197
00:12:22,189 --> 00:12:26,199
The expert involvement can shrink
over time, but it could never be

198
00:12:26,199 --> 00:12:31,159
zero, so we still need a clear kind
of definition of what good actually

199
00:12:31,159 --> 00:12:33,799
means, and we need basic sanity checks.

200
00:12:34,259 --> 00:12:39,059
So reliable baseline this
lets you improve the real task

201
00:12:39,059 --> 00:12:40,509
summer… So the summarization.

202
00:12:40,519 --> 00:12:45,809
So when we want to improve the real task
in an automated, repeatable way, we want

203
00:12:45,809 --> 00:12:47,929
to use, This, we want to use the baseline.

204
00:12:48,879 --> 00:12:49,289
Yes.

205
00:12:49,679 --> 00:12:52,959
And what's s- one of the
strength of our approach is we

206
00:12:52,959 --> 00:12:55,109
use exactly the same methods.

207
00:12:55,369 --> 00:13:00,439
We use exactly the same metrics for human
evaluated scores and LLM as a judge.

208
00:13:00,789 --> 00:13:04,569
So therefore, the comparison
between them could be meaningful.

209
00:13:05,539 --> 00:13:07,939
And I'm already here at my end.

210
00:13:08,049 --> 00:13:12,439
So the key takeaways that I want you
to pay attention to is that LLM as a

211
00:13:12,439 --> 00:13:16,689
judge can be a very useful evaluation
tool if you set it up properly

212
00:13:16,689 --> 00:13:18,409
and understand its limitations.

213
00:13:19,019 --> 00:13:21,899
Good practice is to customize
your metrics to the task.

214
00:13:21,909 --> 00:13:25,299
So depending on what task you have at
hand, you can customize the metrics.

215
00:13:25,969 --> 00:13:32,209
Then you also want the score humans and
the judge on exactly the same dimensions,

216
00:13:32,369 --> 00:13:34,319
then the agreement is meaningful.

217
00:13:34,859 --> 00:13:39,969
And the last point here is that
we need experts in the loop.

218
00:13:39,999 --> 00:13:41,159
We need a human in the loop.

219
00:13:41,209 --> 00:13:46,489
Their involvement could be decreased,
could be shrinked, but we still need them.

220
00:13:46,559 --> 00:13:50,289
We are not yet at the point where
we can eliminate them altogether.

221
00:13:50,819 --> 00:13:53,069
So that would be all from my side.

222
00:13:53,099 --> 00:13:56,789
Thank you very much for your
attention, and I'm open for questions.

223
00:13:57,189 --> 00:13:57,719
Thank you.

